    "## Restoration\n",
    "\n",
    "Image Restoration is the operation of taking a corrupt/noisy image and estimating the clean, original image. Corruption may come in many forms such as motion blur, noise and camera mis-focus; these can be categorized as either convolutional noise or additive noise.\n",
    "\n",
    "Image restoration is different from image enhancement in that the latter is designed to emphasize features of the image that make the image more pleasing to the observer, but not necessarily to produce realistic data from a scientific point of view. Image enhancement techniques (like contrast stretching or de-blurring by a nearest neighbor procedure) provided by imaging packages use no a priori model of the process that created the image. See also https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_restoration."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x1c1fe54be0>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from scipy.signal import convolve2d\n",
    "from skimage import color, restoration\n",
    "\n",
    "astro_original = color.rgb2gray(data.astronaut()) # convert color photo to grayscale\n",
    "\n",
    "# corrupt it\n",
    "astro = astro_original.copy()\n",
    "if 1:  # convolutional noise\n",
    "    psf = np.ones((5, 5)) / 25 # point spread function\n",
    "    astro = convolve2d(astro, psf, 'same')\n",
    "if 1:  # additive noise\n",
    "    astro += 0.25 * astro.std() * np.random.standard_normal(astro.shape)\n",
    "\n",
    "# restore it\n",
    "#deconvolved, _ = restoration.unsupervised_wiener(astro, psf)  # self-tuning\n",
    "deconvolved = restoration.denoise_wavelet(astro)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, figsize=(16,6))\n",
    "ax[0].imshow(astro_original)\n",
    "ax[0].axis('off')\n",
    "ax[0].set_title('Original')\n",
    "ax[1].imshow(astro, vmin=deconvolved.min(), vmax=deconvolved.max())\n",
    "ax[1].axis('off')\n",
    "ax[1].set_title('Data')\n",
    "ax[2].imshow(deconvolved)\n",
    "ax[2].axis('off')\n",
    "ax[2].set_title('Restored')\n",
    "fig.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.02)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "## Radon Transform\n",
    "In computed tomography, the tomography reconstruction problem is to obtain a tomographic slice image from a set of projections. A projection is formed by drawing a set of parallel rays through the 2D object of interest, assigning the integral of the objects contrast along each ray to a single pixel in the projection. A single projection of a 2D object is one dimensional. To enable computed tomography reconstruction of the object, several projections must be acquired, each of them corresponding to a different angle between the rays with respect to the object. A collection of projections at several angles is called the Radon transform or sinogram, which is a linear transform of the original image (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radon_transform).\n",
    "\n",
    "The inverse Radon transform is used in computed tomography to reconstruct a 2D image from the measured projections.\n",
    "\n",
    "See also https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tomography."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x1c20159a58>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from skimage.io import imread\n",
    "from skimage import data_dir\n",
    "from skimage.transform import radon, iradon, rescale\n",
    "from skimage.util import pad\n",
    "\n",
    "#image = pad(data.checkerboard()[:49, :49], 25, mode='constant')  # simple\n",
    "image = imread(data_dir + \"/phantom.png\", as_grey=True)  # complex\n",
    "\n",
    "# simulate tomography experiment\n",
    "theta = np.linspace(0., 180., max(image.shape), endpoint=False) # projection angles\n",
    "sinogram = radon(image, theta=theta, circle=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# reconstruction\n",
    "reconstruction_fbp = iradon(sinogram, theta=theta, circle=True) # based on the Filtered-Back-Projection (FBP) \n",
    "\n",
    "fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(12,6))\n",
    "ax1.set_title(\"Original\")\n",
    "ax1.imshow(image, cmap=plt.cm.Greys_r)\n",
    "ax2.set_title(\"Radon transform\\n(Sinogram)\")\n",
    "ax2.set_xlabel(\"Projection angle (deg)\")\n",
    "ax2.set_ylabel(\"Projection position (pixels)\")\n",
    "ax2.imshow(sinogram, cmap=plt.cm.Greys_r, extent=(0, 180, 0, sinogram.shape[0]), aspect='auto')\n",
    "ax3.set_title(\"Reconstruction\\nFiltered back projection\")\n",
    "ax3.imshow(reconstruction_fbp);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Segmentation\n",
    "Segmentation is the process of partitioning a digital image into multiple segments, typically used to locate objects and boundaries (lines, curves, etc.) in images.\n",
    "### Thresholding\n",
    "Thresholding is used to create a binary image. *Otsus method* calculates an optimal threshold (marked by a red line in the histogram below) by maximizing the variance between two classes of pixels, which are separated by the threshold. Equivalently, this threshold minimizes the intra-class variance."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x1c1fc88be0>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from skimage.filters import threshold_otsu\n",
    "\n",
    "image = data.camera()\n",
    "thresh = threshold_otsu(image)\n",
    "binary = image > thresh\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(16, 8))\n",
    "ax1.imshow(image)\n",
    "ax1.set_title('Original')\n",
    "ax1.axis('off')\n",
    "ax2.hist(image.flatten())\n",
    "ax2.set_title('Histogram')\n",
    "ax2.axvline(thresh, color='r')\n",
    "ax3.imshow(binary)\n",
    "ax3.set_title('Thresholded')\n",
    "ax3.axis('off');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Adaptive/Dynamic Thresholding\n",
    "Thresholding is the simplest way to segment objects from a background. If that background is relatively uniform, then you can use a global threshold value to binarize the image by pixel-intensity. If theres large variation in the background intensity, however, adaptive thresholding (a.k.a. local or dynamic thresholding) may produce better results."
   ]
  },
  {

   "execution_count": 15,

    "from skimage.filters import threshold_otsu, threshold_local\n",
    "\n",
    "# global\n",
    "image = data.page()\n",
    "global_thresh = threshold_otsu(image)\n",
    "print(global_thresh)\n",
    "global_image = image > global_thresh\n",
    "# local\n",
    "local_thresh = threshold_local(image, block_size=41, offset=10)\n",
    "print(local_thresh)\n",
    "local_image = image > local_thresh\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, (ax0, ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(ncols=3, figsize=(16, 3))\n",
    "ax0.imshow(image)\n",
    "ax0.set_title('Image')\n",
    "ax1.imshow(global_image)\n",
    "ax1.set_title('Global thresholding')\n",
    "ax2.imshow(local_image)\n",
    "ax2.set_title('Local thresholding');"
   ]

   "source": [
    "### Blob Detection\n",
    "Blobs are bright on dark or dark on bright regions in an image. In this example, blobs are detected using 3 algorithms (most accurate and slowest to least accurate and fastest): Laplacian of Gaussian (LoG), Difference of Gaussian (DoG), and Determinant of Hessian (DoH)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x1c1fbdc5f8>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from skimage.feature import blob_dog, blob_log, blob_doh\n",
    "from skimage.color import rgb2gray\n",
    "\n",
    "image = data.hubble_deep_field()[0:500, 0:500]\n",
    "image_gray = rgb2gray(image)\n",
    "plt.imshow(image_gray);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x1c201590b8>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "blobs_log = blob_log(image_gray, max_sigma=30, num_sigma=10, threshold=.1)\n",
    "blobs_dog = blob_dog(image_gray, max_sigma=30, threshold=.1)\n",
    "blobs_doh = blob_doh(image_gray, max_sigma=30, threshold=.01)\n",
    "\n",
    "blobs_list = [blobs_log, blobs_dog, blobs_doh]\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(16,8))\n",
    "colors = ['yellow', 'lime', 'red']\n",
    "titles = ['Laplacian of Gaussian', 'Difference of Gaussian',\n",
    "          'Determinant of Hessian']\n",
    "for i, (blobs, color, title) in enumerate(zip(blobs_list, colors, titles)):\n",
    "    ax = axes[i]\n",
    "    ax.set_title(title)\n",
    "    ax.imshow(image, interpolation='nearest')\n",
    "    for blob in blobs:\n",
    "        y, x, r = blob\n",
    "        c = plt.Circle((x, y), r, color=color, linewidth=2, fill=False)\n",
    "        ax.add_patch(c)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Canny edge detector\n",
    "The Canny filter is a multi-stage edge detector. It uses a filter based on the derivative of a Gaussian in order to compute the intensity of the gradients.The Gaussian reduces the effect of noise present in the image. Then, potential edges are thinned down to 1-pixel curves by removing non-maximum pixels of the gradient magnitude. Finally, edge pixels are kept or removed using hysteresis thresholding on the gradient magnitude."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x1c220d9e80>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from skimage import transform, feature, filters\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generate noisy image of a square\n",
    "im = np.zeros((128, 128))\n",
    "im[32:-32, 32:-32] = 1\n",
    "# rotate, blur, and add noise\n",
    "im = transform.rotate(im, 15)\n",
    "im = filters.gaussian(im, 4)\n",
    "im += 0.2 * np.random.random(im.shape)\n",
    "\n",
    "# compute the Canny filter for two values of sigma\n",
    "edges1 = feature.canny(im, sigma=1)\n",
    "edges2 = feature.canny(im, sigma=3)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(16, 4))\n",
    "ax1.imshow(im)\n",
    "ax1.axis('off')\n",
    "ax1.set_title('noisy image')\n",
    "ax2.imshow(edges1)\n",
    "ax2.axis('off')\n",
    "ax2.set_title('Canny filter, $\\sigma=1$')\n",
    "ax3.imshow(edges2)\n",
    "ax3.axis('off')\n",
    "ax3.set_title('Canny filter, $\\sigma=3$');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Template Matching\n",
    "Use template matching to identify the occurrence of an image patch (in this case, a sub-image centered on a single coin). This typically uses a normalized cross-correlation approach."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x1c2369aba8>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from skimage.feature import match_template\n",
    "\n",
    "image = data.coins()\n",
    "coin = image[170:220, 75:130]\n",
    "result = match_template(image, coin)\n",
    "index = np.argmax(result)\n",
    "y, x = np.unravel_index(index, result.shape)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(12, 6))\n",
    "ax1.imshow(coin)\n",
    "ax1.set_axis_off()\n",
    "ax1.set_title('template')\n",
    "\n",
    "ax2.imshow(result)\n",
    "ax2.set_axis_off()\n",
    "ax2.set_title('match result')\n",
    "# highlight matched region\n",
    "ax2.plot(x, y, 'o', markeredgecolor='r', markerfacecolor='none', markersize=10)\n",
    "\n",
    "ax3.imshow(image)\n",
    "ax3.set_axis_off()\n",
    "ax3.set_title('image')\n",
    "# highlight matched region\n",
    "hcoin, wcoin = coin.shape\n",
    "rect = plt.Rectangle((x, y), wcoin, hcoin, edgecolor='r', facecolor='none')\n",
    "ax3.add_patch(rect);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Water-shed segmentation\n",
    "Starting from user-defined markers, the watershed algorithm treats pixels values as a local topography (elevation). The algorithm floods basins from the markers, until basins attributed to different markers meet on watershed lines. In many cases, markers are chosen as local minima of the image, from which basins are flooded.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the example below, two overlapping circles are to be separated. To do so, one computes an image that is the distance to the background. The maxima of this distance (i.e. the minima of the opposite of the distance) are chosen as markers, and the flooding of basins from such markers separates the two circles along a watershed line."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "[(28, 28), (52, 44)]\n",
      "{0, 1, 2}\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x1c21650358>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from scipy.ndimage import distance_transform_edt, label\n",
    "from skimage.morphology import watershed\n",
    "from skimage.feature import peak_local_max\n",
    "\n",
    "# generate a binary image with two overlapping circles\n",
    "x, y = np.indices((80, 80)) # creates the indices of a grid\n",
    "x1, y1, x2, y2 = 28, 28, 44, 52 # circle centers\n",
    "r1, r2 = 16, 20 # circle radii\n",
    "mask_circle1 = (x - x1)**2 + (y - y1)**2 < r1**2\n",
    "mask_circle2 = (x - x2)**2 + (y - y2)**2 < r2**2\n",
    "image = mask_circle1 | mask_circle2 # logical or\n",
    "\n",
    "# compute the distances insides the circles to the background\n",
    "distance = distance_transform_edt(image)\n",
    "\n",
    "# find the local maxima of these distances\n",
    "local_maxima = peak_local_max(distance, indices=False, footprint=np.ones((3, 3)), labels=image)\n",
    "Y, X = np.where(local_maxima)\n",
    "print(list(zip(X, Y)))\n",
    "\n",
    "# uniquely label each maximum \n",
    "markers = label(local_maxima)[0]\n",
    "print(set(markers.flatten()))\n",
    "\n",
    "# watershed segementation\n",
    "labels = watershed(-distance, markers, mask=image)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, (ax0, ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(ncols=3, figsize=(16, 6))\n",
    "ax0.imshow(image)\n",
    "ax0.set_title('Overlapping objects')\n",
    "ax1.imshow(distance)\n",
    "ax1.set_title('Distances')\n",
    "for i in range(len(X)):\n",
    "    ax1.text(X[i], Y[i], markers[X, Y][i], color='r', va='center', ha='center')\n",
    "ax2.imshow(labels, cmap=plt.cm.spectral)\n",
    "ax2.set_title('Separated objects');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Registration\n",
    "Image registration is the process of transforming different sets of data into one coordinate system. Data may be multiple photographs, data from different sensors, times, depths, or viewpoints. Registration is necessary in order to be able to compare or integrate the data obtained from these different measurements.\n",
    "\n",
    "The first problem in registration is to determine the correspondence between a number of *control points* between the source (given) and the target (to be transformed) image; this is usually done by using either intensity- or feature-based algorithms (see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_registration), see the Descripton below.\n",
    "\n",
    "Next, one must choose an algorithm to apply the 2-D control points (warp-field); for example, the 2D piecewise affine (i.e. linear, not elastic or non-rigid) transformation. The transform is based on a Delaunay triangulation of the points to form a mesh. Each triangle is used to find a local affine transform."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x1c2366def0>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from skimage.transform import PiecewiseAffineTransform, warp\n",
    "\n",
    "image = data.astronaut()\n",
    "rows, cols, _ = image.shape\n",
    "\n",
    "# create source control points\n",
    "src_cols = np.linspace(0, cols, 20)\n",
    "src_rows = np.linspace(0, rows, 10)\n",
    "src_rows, src_cols = np.meshgrid(src_rows, src_cols)\n",
    "src = np.dstack([src_cols.flat, src_rows.flat])[0]  # stack array _depth_ wise\n",
    "\n",
    "# create destination control points\n",
    "# add sinusoidal oscillation to row coordinates\n",
    "dst_rows = src[:, 1] - np.sin(np.linspace(0, 3 * np.pi, src.shape[0])) * 50 \n",
    "dst_cols = src[:, 0]\n",
    "dst_rows *= 1.5\n",
    "dst_rows -= 1.5 * 50\n",
    "dst = np.vstack([dst_cols, dst_rows]).T\n",
    "\n",
    "# create the transform, defined by source and target control points \n",
    "tform = PiecewiseAffineTransform()\n",
    "tform.estimate(src, dst)\n",
    "\n",
    "# warp the image based on the transform\n",
    "out_rows = image.shape[0] - 1.5 * 50\n",
    "out_cols = cols\n",
    "out = warp(image, tform, output_shape=(out_rows, out_cols))\n",
    "\n",
    "# plots\n",
    "fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(16,4))\n",
    "ax1.imshow(image)\n",
    "ax1.plot(src[:, 0], src[:, 1], '.r', alpha=0.4)\n",
    "ax1.axis((0, cols, rows, 0))\n",
    "\n",
    "ax2.plot(src_cols, src_rows, 'r.')\n",
    "ax2.plot(dst_cols, dst_rows, 'g.')\n",
    "\n",
    "ax3.imshow(out)\n",
    "ax3.plot(tform.inverse(src)[:, 0], tform.inverse(src)[:, 1], '.g', alpha=0.4)\n",
    "ax3.axis((0, out_cols, out_rows, 0));"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Description\n",
    "Good descriptors of images usually focus on basic elementary features such as: color, texture, shape, and motion. Example algorithms are:\n",
    "\n",
    "* Dense \"DAISY\" feature description, based on gradient orientation histograms\n",
    "* GLCM Texture feature classification using Grey Level Co-occurrence Matrices (GLCMs).\n",
    "\n",
    "These and more algorithms are available in the module.\n",
    "\n",
    "There are also python bindings to the well-known OpenCV library (http://opencv.org), more information is here: https://opencv-python-tutroals.readthedocs.io"
   ]
